Slice the fat on the @pork belly{700%g} into criss-crosses and season with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

Lay the pieces in a cold #frying pan{} fat-side down, turn the heat to medium-high and cook for ~{10-15%minutes}.

> The more you score the fat, the quicker the fat will 'render' (that's a cheffy term for melting the fat!).

For a quick option, heat the oven to 200 degrees. Transfer the pork belly from the #pan{} to a #baking tray{}, fat-side up (keep the pan with the pork belly fat, as we'll use it later for the sauce). Mix the @honey{2%tbsp} and the @spiced honey mustard{2%tbsp} and rub half of it over the scored fat. Put them into the oven for ~{20%minutes}, then remove and allow to rest for at least ~{5%minutes}.

If you have time, take the slower option by heating your oven to 180 degrees. Transfer the pork belly from the pan to a baking tray, fat-side up (keep the pan with the pork belly fat, as we'll use it later for the sauce). Mix the honey and the spiced honey mustard and rub half of it all over the scored fat. Put them into the oven for ~{45-60%minutes}, then remove and allow to rest for at least ~{5%minutes}.

Boil a large #pot{} of water on medium-high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Peel the @potatoes{2} and chop into 2cm cubes. Cook in the boiling water for ~{10-15%minutes} until cooked through, then drain and mash. Stir in @milk{1/2%cup}, @?butter{1%tbsp}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and a few grinds of @black pepper{}.

Put the frying pan you used for the pork back on medium heat. Once the fat in the pan melts, add the @flour{2%tbsp} and stir to scrape off any bits from the pan. Dissolve the @chicken stock pot{1} in @boiling water{300%ml} and gradually add to the pan whilst giving it all a good stir.

Bubble this sauce over medium heat until it has reduced by half. Add the remaining honey and spiced honey mustard and taste for seasoning and add more @salt{} or @pepper{} as you like.

> Add the juices that have leaked out of the rested meat for an extra hit of flavour.

While the sauce is reducing and potatoes are boiling, boil another pot of water with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Cut and discard the ends from the @green beans{1%handful}. Cook in the boiling water for ~{3-4%minutes} or until 'al dente'.

> 'Al dente' simply means they have a little bit of crunch left in the middle.

Slice the pork belly into 1cm slices. Divide the mash and green beans between your plates, top with slices of the pork belly and drizzle over the sauce.